    The [Chaplain–Medic massacre](/Chaplain%E2%80%93Medic_massacre) is a somber chapter in the annals of the [Korean War](/Korean_War), an event that unfolded on July 16, 1950. The precise location remains a point of local contention, with some accounts placing it on a mountain overlooking the village of Tuman (now known as Duman-ri, [Geumnam-myeon, Sejong City](/Geumnam-myeon,_Sejong_City)), while others, primarily [South Korean](/South_Korea) natives, insist it occurred on a mountain above the adjacent village of Yongdam-ri. Regardless of the exact coordinates of this tragedy, the facts remain stark: thirty critically wounded, unarmed [United States Army](/United_States_Army) (US) soldiers, along with an equally unarmed [chaplain](/Chaplain), were brutally murdered by elements of the [Korean People's Army](/Korean_People%27s_Army) (KPA) during the intense and chaotic [Battle of the Kum River](/Battle_of_the_Kum_River).

    Prior to this horrific incident, troops from the US [19th Infantry Regiment](/19th_Infantry_Regiment_(United_States)), a component of the [24th Infantry Division](/24th_Infantry_Division_(United_States)), found themselves operating along the [Kum River](/Kum_River). Their supply lines were severed by a formidable [roadblock](/Roadblock) established by KPA forces from the [3rd Division](/3rd_Division_(North_Korea)). This obstruction proved stubbornly resistant to American efforts to dislodge it, ultimately forcing the US troops to abandon their conventional routes and instead navigate the treacherous, nearby mountains in a desperate attempt to evacuate their wounded personnel. A grim situation made infinitely worse. ( [Full article...](/Chaplain%E2%80%93Medic_massacre) )

*   #### Image 2
    Kolob Canyons from the end of Kolob Canyons Road. Stream erosion has incised the Kolob Plateau to form canyons that expose the red-orange colored Navajo Sandstone and other formations.

    The [geology of the Zion and Kolob canyons area](/Geology_of_the_Zion_and_Kolob_canyons_area) presents a rather compelling narrative, a visual chronicle etched into the very rock of [Zion National Park](/Zion_National_Park) in the U.S. state of [Utah](/Utah). Within this dramatic landscape, nine distinct exposed [formations](/Formation_(geology)) are identifiable, each layer telling a story spanning approximately 150 million years. This vast temporal canvas predominantly covers the [Mesozoic](/Mesozoic) Era, a period marked by extensive [sedimentation](/Sedimentation) across what would eventually become this particular segment of [North America](/Geology_of_North_America). These formations, an integral piece of the larger geological puzzle known as the [Grand Staircase](/Grand_Staircase), were laid down in an array of ancient environments. Imagine the warm, shallow, prehistoric seas that once covered the regions now defined by the Kaibab and Moenkopi formations, giving way to the bustling [streams](/Stream) and serene [lakes](/Lake) responsible for the Chinle, Moenave, and Kayenta formations. Further epochs brought forth vast, arid [deserts](/Desert), contributing to the iconic Navajo and Temple Cap formations, while the dry, near-shore conditions shaped the Carmel Formation.

    Following these prolonged periods of deposition, the entire [Colorado Plateau](/Colorado_Plateau) began a slow, inexorable ascent, gradually elevating these ancient layers far above their original points of formation. This tectonic uplift had a profound effect, dramatically increasing the [stream gradient](/Stream_gradient) of the ancient rivers and countless other smaller watercourses flowing across the nascent [plateau](/Plateau). These newly invigorated, faster-moving streams, seizing upon the structural weaknesses of uplift-created joints in the rock, systematically eroded away all [Cenozoic](/Cenozoic)-aged formations and relentlessly carved out the deep, majestic gorges that define the region today. [Zion Canyon](/Zion_National_Park), for instance, stands as a monumental testament to the relentless power of the North Fork of the [Virgin River](/Virgin_River), which sculpted its grandeur through this very process. In the later stages of this geological drama, sporadic [lava](/Lava) flows and dramatic [cinder cones](/Cinder_cone) erupted, blanketing and reshaping portions of the area, adding yet another layer to its complex and violent history. ( [Full article...](/Geology_of_the_Zion_and_Kolob_canyons_area) )

*   #### Image 3

    Postcard view of Beach Boulevard and the Hotel Galvez, early 1940s

    The [Free State of Galveston](/Free_State_of_Galveston), a rather evocative, if entirely satirical, moniker, was bestowed upon the [coastal](/Gulf_Coast_of_the_United_States) city of [Galveston](/Galveston,_Texas) in the [U.S.](/United_States) [state](/U.S._state) of [Texas](/Texas) during the vibrant, yet illicit, early-to-mid-20th century. Even today, the phrase occasionally resurfaces, used to conjure the distinct and often scandalous cultural spirit and historical legacy of that bygone era.

    It was during the hedonistic flourish of the [Roaring Twenties](/Roaring_Twenties) that [Galveston Island](/Galveston,_Texas) truly blossomed, transforming into a coveted [resort town](/Resort_town) that lured celebrities and thrill-seekers from across the nation. The island's magnetic pull was undeniable, largely fueled by a thriving underground economy of gambling, freely flowing [illegal liquor](/Rum-running), and a host of other vice-oriented enterprises that formed the very bedrock of its burgeoning tourism industry. The "Free State" label wasn't merely a catchy phrase; it embodied a profound local conviction that Galveston existed beyond the perceived repressive social mores and stringent laws imposed by the rest of Texas and the [United States](/United_States).

    Two towering figures, almost mythical in their local influence, dominated this era: the [businessmen](/Entrepreneurship), shrewd [power brokers](/Power_broker_(politics)), and undeniable [crime](/Organized_crime) bosses, [Sam](/Sam_Maceo) and [Rosario Maceo](/Rosario_Maceo). These brothers expertly managed the island's premier casinos and clubs, their tentacles deeply entwined within local politics and the lucrative tourism sector. The astonishing success of these illicit ventures, despite their undeniable illegality, was a direct consequence of a pervasive laxity in societal attitudes and, more critically, in governmental enforcement, both on the island itself and throughout the surrounding county. In one of the most famously audacious examples of this systemic complacency, a state committee, dispatched to investigate the rampant gambling at the legendary [Balinese Room](/Balinese_Room), was met with a breathtakingly simple, yet utterly effective, deflection from the local [sheriff](/Sheriffs_in_the_United_States). He coolly informed the committee that he had refrained from raiding the establishment because it was, in his words, a "private club" and, crucially, he was not a "member." Such was the brazen charm of the "Free State." ( [Full article...](/Free_State_of_Galveston) )

*   #### Image 4

    The [Albany Charter half dollar](/Albany_Charter_half_dollar), sometimes known as the Albany-Dongan half dollar or simply the Albany half dollar, represents a fascinating artifact of American numismatic history. This commemorative [half dollar](/Half_dollar_(United_States_coin)) was meticulously struck by the [United States Bureau of the Mint](/United_States_Bureau_of_the_Mint) in 1936, a year that saw a curious proliferation of such special issues. The coin's intricate design was the work of sculptor [Gertrude K. Lathrop](/Gertrude_K._Lathrop), an artist who, fittingly, resided in [Albany, New York](/Albany,_New_York)'s state capital, the very city the coin sought to honor.

    The year 1936 proved to be something of a boom for commemorative coinage, with Congress giving its imprimatur to numerous issues, many of which, like the Albany piece, held primarily local significance. City officials in Albany, eager to mark the 250th anniversary of the 1686 grant of their [municipal charter](/Dongan_Charter) by [Thomas Dongan](/Thomas_Dongan), the then-governor of colonial New York, lobbied for this particular coin. The authorizing legislation navigated its way through Congress with remarkably little opposition, though amendments were wisely appended to include protections for coin collectors, aiming to prevent the speculative abuses that had marred earlier commemorative issues. Lathrop's artistic contributions have, by and large, garnered considerable praise. On one side of the coin, she rendered a meticulously detailed beaver, reportedly modeled from life – an animal that, perhaps not coincidentally, features prominently on Albany's official city seal. The obverse side depicts the key figures involved in the momentous charter grant. Following the requisite approval of these designs by the [Commission of Fine Arts](/Commission_of_Fine_Arts), the [Philadelphia Mint](/Philadelphia_Mint) proceeded to strike 25,013 Albany half dollars in October 1936. This total included 13 special pieces designated for testing by the rigorous [Assay Commission](/Assay_Commission), ensuring the coin's metallic integrity and composition. ( [Full article...](/Albany_Charter_half_dollar) )

*   #### Image 5

    In 1840, [William Henry Harrison](/William_Henry_Harrison) ascended to the highest office in the land, elected as [President of the United States](/President_of_the_United_States). Harrison, a figure whose career spanned military generalship and service as a [United States Senator](/United_States_Senate) from Ohio, successfully unseated the incumbent president, [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [Martin Van Buren](/Martin_Van_Buren), in a campaign that, for its time, truly broke new ground in the landscape of American politics. Among its many "firsts," Harrison's triumph marked the inaugural occasion that the [Whig Party](/Whig_Party_(United_States)) secured a presidential election victory. However, the taste of victory was fleeting. A mere month after assuming the weighty responsibilities of office, Harrison tragically died. His running mate, [John Tyler](/John_Tyler), thus inherited the presidency, serving out the remainder of the term. Yet, Tyler swiftly diverged from the established Whig agenda, a political schism so profound that it led to his expulsion from the party that had elevated him.

    Harrison himself was born into considerable wealth in 1773. He embarked on a military career, leveraging his father, [Benjamin Harrison V](/Benjamin_Harrison_V)'s, influential connections to secure political office on the burgeoning frontier. After a decade spent as governor of [Indiana Territory](/Indiana_Territory), Harrison forged his reputation through his campaigns against Native American tribes, most notably at the 1811 [Battle of Tippecanoe](/Battle_of_Tippecanoe). With the onset of the [War of 1812](/War_of_1812), he turned his military prowess against the British, achieving decisive victories over both at the [Battle of the Thames](/Battle_of_the_Thames) in 1813. Following the cessation of hostilities, his political career continued its upward trajectory; he was elected to Congress representing Ohio and subsequently held a variety of public offices over the ensuing two decades. A regional Whig candidate in the [1836 United States presidential election](/1836_United_States_presidential_election), he placed second to Van Buren, a defeat that did little to dampen his presidential ambitions. He continued his relentless pursuit of the highest office, finally achieving it four years later. ( [Full article...](/William_Henry_Harrison_1840_presidential_campaign) )

*   #### Image 6
    [Kitty Marion](/Kitty_Marion) (born Katherina Maria Schäfer, on March 12, 1871 – died October 9, 1944) was a woman who, despite the restrictive social norms of her era, dedicated her life to activism. Her causes were significant: she was a vocal proponent for [women's suffrage](/Women%27s_suffrage) and a fierce advocate for [birth control](/Birth_control). Born in the [German Empire](/German_Empire), she made the pivotal decision to immigrate to England in 1886 at the tender age of fifteen, embarking on a new life that would soon be defined by her unwavering commitment to social change.

    In the latter half of the 19th century, Marion carved out a career for herself singing in the bustling [music halls](/Music_hall) across the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom). It was within this vibrant, yet often exploitative, entertainment industry that she gained notoriety, not just for her performances, but for her courage in drawing public attention to the pervasive sexism and rampant sexual assaults that were an unfortunate, yet common, reality of the business.

    Marion emerged as a prominent and indefatigable member of the [British suffrage movement](/British_suffrage_movement), a formidable campaign dedicated to securing the fundamental right to vote for women. Her journey into activism began relatively modestly, by diligently selling copies of the "Votes for Women" newspaper. However, her commitment quickly escalated, propelling her into the more militant and often dangerous tactics of protest, including acts of vandalism and participation in riots. She became one of several suffragettes who, driven by a desperate urgency for change, engaged in a controversial campaign of [bombing and arson attacks throughout Britain](/Suffragette_bombing_and_arson_campaign). For these actions, Marion was repeatedly convicted and incarcerated, serving multiple jail sentences for arson and bombing. Her resilience in the face of state suppression was remarkable; while imprisoned, she endured over two hundred instances of [force-feeding](/Force-feeding) during her courageous hunger strikes, a testament to her unyielding resolve. ( [Full article...](/Kitty_Marion) )

*   #### Image 7

    270 Park Avenue in April 2008

    [270 Park Avenue](/270_Park_Avenue_(1960%E2%80%932021)), a structure once known by the more descriptive titles of the JPMorgan Chase Tower and the Union Carbide Building, was a prominent [skyscraper](/Skyscraper) that commanded a significant presence in the [Midtown Manhattan](/Midtown_Manhattan) neighborhood of [New York City](/New_York_City), [United States](/United_States). Erected in 1960, initially to house the operations of the chemical giant [Union Carbide](/Union_Carbide), its design was the collaborative effort of the esteemed architects [Gordon Bunshaft](/Gordon_Bunshaft) and [Natalie de Blois](/Natalie_de_Blois) from the renowned firm [Skidmore, Owings & Merrill](/Skidmore,_Owings_%26_Merrill) (SOM). This imposing 52-story edifice, soaring to a height of 707 feet (215 meters), later transitioned to become the global headquarters for the financial behemoth [JPMorgan Chase](/JPMorgan_Chase). Its existence, however, was ultimately finite. In 2021, it faced a rather ignominious fate, undergoing demolition to clear the way for a more contemporary, and indeed [taller skyscraper at the same address](/270_Park_Avenue_(2021%E2%80%93present)). At the time of its systematic dismantling, the Union Carbide Building held the dubious distinction of being the [tallest voluntarily demolished building](/List_of_tallest_voluntarily_demolished_buildings) in the entire world. A testament to the relentless, and often wasteful, march of urban development.

    The building's footprint was substantial, occupying a full [city block](/City_block) meticulously delineated by [Madison Avenue](/Madison_Avenue), 48th Street, [Park Avenue](/Park_Avenue), and [47th Street](/47th_Street_(Manhattan)). Architecturally, it was conceived as a dual-component structure: a towering 52-story section that proudly faced Park Avenue to the east, complemented by a more modest 12-story annex situated on the Madison Avenue side to the west. Both sections were thoughtfully enveloped by public plazas, offering a degree of urban breathing room. A particularly challenging engineering feat involved constructing approximately two-thirds of 270 Park Avenue directly over two levels of subterranean railroad tracks. These tracks served as vital arteries, feeding directly into the majestic [Grand Central Terminal](/Grand_Central_Terminal) located just to the south. This unique structural constraint not only precluded the construction of a conventional basement beneath the majority of the site but also necessitated that the building's main lobby be positioned one story above ground level. Union Carbide's internal offices were meticulously designed around a precise grid of 5-by-5-foot (1.5 by 1.5 meter) modules, emphasizing modularity and adaptability. The interior spaces boasted flexible furnishings and partitions, complemented by innovative luminous ceilings, all contributing to a modern and efficient workspace. Throughout its lifespan, the Union Carbide Building garnered a rather mixed reception from critics and the public alike. Nonetheless, the innovative inclusion of its public plazas played a significant, and often overlooked, role in influencing the seminal 1961 Zoning Resolution, which sought to encourage similar urban amenities in subsequent developments. ( [Full article...](/270_Park_Avenue_(1960%E2%80%932021)) )

*   #### Image 8
    [In Utero](/In_Utero) stands as the third and, as fate would have it, final studio album released by the American [rock](/Rock_music) band [Nirvana](/Nirvana_(band)). It saw its debut in September 1993, under the imprimatur of [DGC Records](/DGC_Records). Following their explosive, mainstream breakthrough with the preceding album, [Nevermind](/Nevermind) (1991), Nirvana deliberately sought a different sonic direction for its successor. They enlisted the distinct talents of [Steve Albini](/Steve_Albini) to record *In Utero*, aiming for a sound that was deliberately more complex, raw, and abrasive, a deliberate return to the grittier aesthetic that characterized their earlier, pre-*Nevermind* work. While the principal songwriter, [Kurt Cobain](/Kurt_Cobain), notoriously described the album as "very impersonal," a closer listen reveals that many of its lyrical themes subtly, or not so subtly, allude to the intricate and often painful facets of his personal life, echoing the profound feelings of angst that had permeated *Nevermind*.

    The recording sessions for *In Utero* were a concentrated burst of creative energy, completed over a mere two weeks in February 1993 at [Pachyderm Studios](/Pachyderm_Studios), nestled in [Cannon Falls, Minnesota](/Cannon_Falls,_Minnesota). Upon the conclusion of recording, a flurry of rumors began to circulate, suggesting that DGC might hesitate to release the album due to Albini's notoriously abrasive and defiantly uncommercial production style. To navigate these concerns and achieve a sound deemed more palatable for both the band and the label, the album underwent a mastering process by the renowned [Bob Ludwig](/Bob_Ludwig). Furthermore, Nirvana subsequently brought in producer [Scott Litt](/Scott_Litt) to remix three crucial tracks destined for single release: "[All Apologies](/All_Apologies)", "[Heart-Shaped Box](/Heart-Shaped_Box)", and "[Pennyroyal Tea](/Pennyroyal_Tea)". These post-production adjustments aimed to temper some of Albini's more stark choices, ultimately shaping the album's final, influential sound. ( [Full article...](/In_Utero) )

*   #### Image 9

    The [blue whale](/Blue_whale) (*Balaenoptera musculus*) is not merely a creature of the deep; it is a colossal marvel, a [marine mammal](/Marine_mammal) and a prime example of a [baleen whale](/Baleen_whale). Its dimensions are staggering: reaching a maximum confirmed length of between 29.9 and 30.5 meters (98–100 feet) and tipping the scales at an astonishing 190–200 tonnes (190–200 long tons; 210–220 short tons), it holds the undisputed title as the [largest animal known to have ever existed](/Largest_and_heaviest_animals) on Earth, dwarfing even the most immense dinosaurs. The blue whale's elongated and gracefully slender body typically displays various nuanced shades of grayish-blue on its dorsal surface, transitioning to a somewhat lighter hue underneath, providing a subtle camouflage in the vast ocean depths. Current scientific understanding recognizes four distinct [subspecies](/Subspecies): *B. m. musculus*, found in the frigid waters of the North Atlantic and North Pacific; *B. m. intermedia*, inhabiting the Southern Ocean; *B. m. brevicauda*, famously known as the [pygmy blue whale](/Pygmy_blue_whale), which prefers the warmer currents of the Indian Ocean and South Pacific Ocean; and *B. m. indica*, residing in the Northern Indian Ocean. There is also a notable population thriving in the waters off [Chile](/Chile) that scientists are currently investigating, which may very well constitute a fifth, as-yet-unclassified, subspecies.

    In a general migratory pattern, blue whale populations embark on extensive journeys between their abundant summer feeding grounds, typically located near the poles where krill is plentiful, and their warmer winter breeding grounds, usually found closer to the tropics. However, the intricacies of their movements are not entirely uniform; there is also compelling evidence of some populations maintaining year-round residencies in certain areas, as well as partial or age- and sex-based migration patterns that deviate from the general rule. Blue whales are quintessential [filter feeders](/Filter_feeder); their diet is remarkably specialized, consisting almost exclusively of tiny [krill](/Krill), which they consume in immense quantities. Socially, they tend to be solitary creatures or gather in small, loose aggregations, and unlike some other cetaceans, they do not exhibit a complex or well-defined social structure beyond the fundamental bonds between a mother and her calf. Their presence in the ocean is often announced by their distinctive [vocalizations](/Whale_vocalization), which possess a remarkably low [fundamental frequency](/Fundamental_frequency) ranging from 8 to 25 Hz. These powerful, resonant sounds may vary significantly based on the specific geographical region, the season, the particular behavior they are engaged in, and even the time of day. Despite their immense size, blue whales are not without predators; surprisingly, [orcas](/Orca) (killer whales) stand as their only known natural adversaries, a testament to the orca's predatory prowess. ( [Full article...](/Blue_whale) )

*   #### Image 10

    AA11's path from [Logan International Airport](/Logan_International_Airport) in [Boston](/Boston) to [New York City](/New_York_City)

    [American Airlines Flight 11](/American_Airlines_Flight_11) was a seemingly ordinary domestic [passenger flight](/Airline) that, on the morning of September 11, 2001, was catastrophically transformed into an instrument of terror. It was hijacked by five [al-Qaeda](/Al-Qaeda) terrorists, becoming a central component of the coordinated [September 11 attacks](/September_11_attacks). The hijacked airliner was then deliberately crashed into the [North Tower](/1_World_Trade_Center_(1971%E2%80%932001)) of the iconic [World Trade Center](/World_Trade_Center_(1973%E2%80%932001)) complex in [New York City](/New_York_City). This act resulted in the immediate deaths of everyone aboard the flight and, tragically, led to the demise of over a thousand people trapped within the top 18 stories of the skyscraper, in addition to countless others affected below the impact zone. The impact of Flight 11 stands as the [deadliest of the four suicide attacks](/Casualties_of_the_September_11_attacks) executed that devastating morning, not only in terms of those aboard the plane but also the fatalities on the ground. It remains the single deadliest act of terrorism in human history and, horrifyingly, the [deadliest plane crash of all time](/List_of_deadliest_aircraft_accidents_and_incidents). The aircraft involved, a [Boeing 767-200ER](/Boeing_767) carrying 92 passengers and crew, was performing [American Airlines](/American_Airlines)' routine scheduled morning [transcontinental service](/Transcontinental_flight), having departed from [Boston Logan International Airport](/Logan_International_Airport) in [Massachusetts](/Massachusetts) with its destination set as [Los Angeles International Airport](/Los_Angeles_International_Airport) in [California](/California).

    The ill-fated aircraft departed its runway at 07:59 Eastern Daylight Time. A mere fifteen minutes after takeoff, the [hijackers](/Hijackers_in_the_September_11_attacks) executed their violent plan. They inflicted injuries upon two flight attendants, brutally murdered one passenger, and successfully breached the cockpit, forcibly relocating the remaining passengers and crew to the rear of the aircraft. The assailants then attacked both pilots, allowing the lead hijacker, [Mohamed Atta](/Mohamed_Atta), to seize control of the aircraft. Air traffic controllers, observing the sudden lack of communication and erratic flight path, quickly suspected the flight was in distress. Their suspicions were grimly confirmed when Atta's announcement, intended for the terrified hostages onboard, was accidentally transmitted to air traffic control instead of through the aircraft's public address system. Furthermore, two courageous flight attendants managed to establish contact with [American Airlines](/American_Airlines) personnel on the ground, relaying crucial information pertinent to the unfolding crisis, including the casualties already sustained by the crew and passengers. These desperate communications provided the first terrifying glimpses into the unfolding tragedy. ( [Full article...](/American_Airlines_Flight_11) )

*   #### Image 11

    Native Solomon Islanders guide US 2nd Marine Raiders in pursuit of Japanese forces on Guadalcanal in November 1942

    [Carlson's patrol](/Carlson%E2%80%93Medic_massacre), also known by the more evocative titles of The Long Patrol or Carlson's long patrol, was a grueling [military operation](/Military_operation) undertaken by the [2nd Marine Raider Battalion](/Marine_Raiders) under the resolute command of [Evans Carlson](/Evans_Carlson). This particular action unfolded during the brutal [Guadalcanal campaign](/Guadalcanal_campaign) against the entrenched [Imperial Japanese Army](/Imperial_Japanese_Army), spanning from November 6 to December 4, 1942. The core objective of the operation was to intercept and decisively engage Japanese forces, specifically those under the command of [Toshinari Shōji](/Toshinari_Sh%C5%8Dji). These Japanese units were in the process of [escaping from an attempted encirclement](/Koli_Point_action) in the Koli Point area on [Guadalcanal](/Guadalcanal), desperately striving to rejoin other Japanese army formations positioned on the opposite side of the American Lunga perimeter.

    Over a relentless period of 29 days, the 2nd Raiders engaged in a series of intense, small-unit skirmishes, a testament to the unforgiving jungle warfare prevalent in the Pacific theater. In these engagements, the Raiders inflicted heavy casualties upon the Japanese, killing nearly 500 soldiers, while suffering comparatively lighter losses of 16 killed. However, the toll of the jungle environment was significant, with many Raiders succumbing to debilitating diseases, a common adversary in the tropical conditions. Beyond the human cost, the patrol achieved a notable tactical success: they managed to capture a Japanese field gun that had been relentlessly harassing [Henderson Field](/Henderson_Field_(Guadalcanal)), the crucial [Allied](/Allies_of_World_War_II) airfield located at [Lunga Point](/Lunga_Point) on Guadalcanal. This protracted patrol remains a significant example of sustained, deep-jungle combat during World War II. ( [Full article...](/Carlson%E2%80%93Medic_massacre) )

*   #### Image 12

    A U.S. Army [75 mm pack howitzer](/M116_howitzer) firing at close range at a Japanese position on Hill 260 in March 1944

    The [Bougainville counterattack](/Bougainville_counterattack), also frequently referred to as the Second Battle of Torokina, represents a pivotal, albeit ultimately unsuccessful, Japanese offensive launched against the well-established [Allied](/Allies_of_World_War_II) base situated at [Cape Torokina](/Cape_Torokina) on [Bougainville Island](/Bougainville_Island) during the ferocious [Pacific Theater](/Pacific_War) of [World War II](/World_War_II). This ambitious Japanese assault commenced on March 8, 1944, following months of meticulous, though ultimately flawed, preparation. It was met and decisively repulsed by determined [United States Army](/United_States_Army) forces in a grinding engagement that persisted until March 25. The Japanese attack was severely hampered from its inception by a combination of inaccurate intelligence assessments and a glaring lack of effective planning. Consequently, their forces found themselves significantly outnumbered by the well-entrenched and thoroughly prepared Allied defenders. The outcome was a devastating toll on the Japanese, who suffered severe casualties, while Allied losses remained remarkably light, a testament to their defensive strength and the weaknesses of the Japanese strategy.

    The primary strategic objective of this offensive was nothing less than the complete destruction of the Allied [beachhead](/Beachhead) at Torokina, a crucial logistical hub that also accommodated three strategically vital airfields. The Japanese command operated under the critical misconception that their attacking forces were roughly equivalent in size to the units deployed to defend the Allied positions, a miscalculation that proved fatal. Despite their concerted efforts, none of the three Japanese forces tasked with conducting the attack managed to penetrate deeply into the Allied perimeter. However, this does not diminish the ferocity of the fighting; intense, close-quarters combat raged for control of several key defensive positions, underscoring the determination of both sides. Ultimately, the Allied defenses held firm, securing their foothold on Bougainville. ( [Full article...](/Bougainville_counterattack) )

*   #### Image 13

    Aliso Creek flows underneath the Aliso Creek Road bridge before it enters [Aliso and Wood Canyons Wilderness Park](/Aliso_and_Wood_Canyons_Wilderness_Park).

    [Aliso Creek](/Aliso_Creek_(Orange_County)) is a geographically significant, albeit increasingly urbanized, [stream](/Urban_stream) meandering for 19.8 miles (31.9 kilometers) through the southern expanse of [Orange County](/Orange_County,_California), [California](/California). Its headwaters originate within the pristine confines of the [Cleveland National Forest](/Cleveland_National_Forest), nestled high in the [Santa Ana Mountains](/Santa_Ana_Mountains). From there, it embarks on a generally southwestward journey, ultimately culminating in its discharge into the vast [Pacific Ocean](/Pacific_Ocean) at the picturesque coastal community of [Laguna Beach](/Laguna_Beach,_California). The creek's [watershed](/Drainage_basin) encompasses an area of 34.9 square miles (90 square kilometers) and is fed by a network of seven main [tributaries](/Tributary), each contributing to its flow. As of 2018, this watershed supported a considerable population of 144,000 residents, distributed across seven incorporated cities, highlighting the intense human interaction with this natural system.

    Geologically, Aliso Creek traverses highly erosive marine [sedimentary rock](/Sedimentary_rock) formations, dating from the late [Eocene](/Eocene) to the [Pliocene](/Pliocene) epochs. What we now recognize as the Aliso Creek watershed began its existence submerged beneath the Pacific Ocean, only to be gradually uplifted by tectonic forces as recently as 10 million years ago. A subsequent, significant geological event occurred approximately 1.2 million years ago, when the [San Joaquin Hills](/San_Joaquin_Hills) began their slow ascent directly in the path of the existing Aliso Creek. Periodically swollen by the wetter climatic conditions characteristic of past [glacial periods](/Glacial_period), the creek, with its enhanced erosive power, meticulously carved the deep [water gap](/Water_gap) that is famously known today as [Aliso Canyon](/Aliso_Canyon). This impressive canyon now forms the dominant natural feature of the expansive [Aliso and Wood Canyons Wilderness Park](/Aliso_and_Wood_Canyons_Wilderness_Park), a testament to the enduring power of water and geological time. ( [Full article...](/Aliso_Creek_(Orange_County)) )

*   #### Image 14

    Bottled maple syrup

    [Maple syrup](/Maple_syrup) is not merely a breakfast condiment; it is a distinctly sweet [syrup](/Syrup) derived with remarkable simplicity from the [sap](/Sap) of [maple](/Maple) trees. In regions characterized by cold climates, these deciduous giants possess an ingenious natural mechanism: prior to the onset of winter's deep freeze, they diligently store [starch](/Starch) within their trunks and extensive root systems. As late winter transitions into the nascent days of spring, this stored starch undergoes a biochemical transformation, converting into [sugar](/Sugar] that then rises, carried by the sap, through the tree's vascular system. The process of extraction is elegantly straightforward: maple trees are "tapped" by drilling small, shallow holes into their trunks, allowing the precious sap to flow out and be collected. This collected sap, a watery, subtly sweet liquid, is then subjected to a heating process designed to [evaporate](/Evaporation) a significant portion of its water content, leaving behind the rich, concentrated syrup we recognize.

    The origins of maple syrup production are deeply rooted in the traditions of the [Indigenous people](/Indigenous_peoples_of_North_America) of Northeastern North America. These early inhabitants not only discovered the sap's potential but also developed the initial methods for its processing, long before European arrival. The practice was subsequently adopted by European settlers, who, over generations, gradually refined and adapted the production techniques, integrating new tools and understandings. The modern era saw significant advancements, with technological improvements in the 1970s further streamlining and enhancing the efficiency of syrup processing, leading to the sophisticated operations seen today. Presently, a staggering proportion – almost all – of the world's maple syrup is produced in just two nations: [Canada](/Canada) and the [United States](/United_States), a testament to their abundant maple forests and enduring cultural practice. ( [Full article...](/Maple_syrup) )

*   #### Image 15

    Congress by Charles Ware, 1816

    USS Congress was a formidable three-masted [heavy frigate](/Heavy_frigate), holding the distinction of being one of the [first six ships commissioned by the newly created United States Navy](/Original_six_frigates_of_the_United_States_Navy). Constructed with precision by the master shipbuilder [James Hackett](/James_Hackett_(shipbuilder)) at the [Portsmouth Naval Shipyard](/Portsmouth_Naval_Shipyard), she was majestically launched on August 15, 1799. Though [nominally rated](/Rating_system_of_the_Royal_Navy) as a 38-gun frigate, a common practice of the era, she often carried a more substantial armament, frequently bristling with up to 48 guns. The name "Congress" itself was selected from a curated list of ten names presented to President [George Washington](/George_Washington) by Secretary of War [Timothy Pickering](/Timothy_Pickering) in March 1795, a choice reflecting the nascent nation's democratic ideals. In accordance with the visionary designs of [Joshua Humphreys](/Joshua_Humphreys), who intended these frigates to serve as the young Navy's premier [capital ships](/Capital_ship), *Congress* and her esteemed [sister ships](/Sister_ship) were deliberately engineered to be larger and more heavily armed than the standard frigates prevalent during that period, giving them a distinct advantage.

    Upon her commissioning into the newly formed [United States Navy](/United_States_Navy), *Congress*'s initial duties were critical: she was tasked with providing essential protection for American merchant shipping navigating the treacherous waters of the [Quasi-War](/Quasi_War) with [France](/France), and later, with engaging and ultimately defeating the notorious [Barbary pirates](/Barbary_pirates) in the [First Barbary War](/First_Barbary_War). During the tumultuous [War of 1812](/War_of_1812), she embarked on several extended, arduous cruises, often sailing in concert with her [sister ship](/Sister_ship) *President*. In these operations, she successfully captured or assisted in the capture of an impressive twenty British merchant vessels, disrupting enemy trade and contributing to the American war effort. However, by the end of 1813, a critical shortage of necessary repair materials compelled her to be [placed in reserve](/Reserve_fleet) for the remainder of the conflict. Her service resumed in 1815 for the [Second Barbary War](/Second_Barbary_War), conducting vital patrols through 1816. The 1820s saw *Congress* actively engaged in suppressing piracy in the [West Indies](/West_Indies), undertaking multiple voyages to [South America](/South_America), and notably, becoming the first U.S. warship to make a diplomatic visit to [China](/China). The final decade of her distinguished service, until her eventual [breaking up](/Ship_breaking) in 1834, was spent as a [receiving ship](/Receiving_ship), a floating barracks for new recruits, marking the end of a remarkable career for one of America's foundational naval vessels. ( [Full article...](/USS_Congress_(1799)) )

*   #### Image 16

    The [Eisenhower dollar](/Eisenhower_dollar) is a one-dollar coin that was officially issued by the [United States Mint](/United_States_Mint) for a period spanning from 1971 to 1978. Its introduction marked a significant moment, as it was the first [coin of that denomination](/Dollar_coin_(United_States)) to be released by the Mint since the conclusion of the [Peace dollar](/Peace_dollar) series in 1935. The coin prominently features the likeness of President [Dwight D. Eisenhower](/Dwight_D._Eisenhower) on its [obverse](/Obverse_and_reverse), a fitting tribute to a revered national figure. The reverse side, in contrast, showcases a stylized image intended to honor the groundbreaking 1969 [Apollo 11](/Apollo_11) Moon mission, capturing a moment of profound national achievement. Both sides of the coin were meticulously designed by [Frank Gasparro](/Frank_Gasparro), with the reverse drawing direct inspiration from the mission patch originally conceived by astronaut [Michael Collins](/Michael_Collins_(astronaut)). Uniquely among large-size U.S. dollar coins, the Eisenhower dollar's circulation strikes contained no silver, a reflection of changing economic realities.

    The mid-1960s saw a critical shift in U.S. coinage policy. In 1965, driven by escalating bullion prices, the Mint began transitioning to striking copper-nickel [clad](/Cladding_(metalworking)) coins, moving away from the precious metal compositions of earlier issues. Despite a three-decade hiatus in the issuance of dollar coins, a legislative push emerged in 1969 to reintroduce this denomination into circulation. Following President Eisenhower's death in March of that year, numerous proposals swiftly arose advocating for him to be honored on the new coin. While these legislative efforts generally enjoyed broad bipartisan support, their enactment was notably delayed by a contentious debate: should the new dollar coin be composed of a base metal, or should it retain a 40% silver content? This dispute reflected a broader tension between practical circulation needs and the desire for a collectible, more valuable coin. A compromise was eventually brokered in 1970, stipulating that the Eisenhower dollar would be struck in base metal for general circulation, while a distinct 40% silver version would be produced specifically for collectors. On December 31, 1970, President [Richard Nixon](/Richard_Nixon), who had served as [vice president](/Vice_President_of_the_United_States) under Eisenhower, signed the crucial legislation, officially authorizing the mintage of this new and symbolically significant coin. ( [Full article...](/Eisenhower_dollar) )

*   #### Image 17
    [U.S. Route 491](/U.S._Route_491) (US 491) is a significant north–south [U.S. Highway](/U.S._Highway) that serves the unique [Four Corners](/Four_Corners) region of the [United States](/United_States). This route came into being in 2003, a direct result of a renumbering initiative that saw its previous designation, U.S. Route 666 (US 666), retired. Under its former, rather infamous designation, the road earned the chilling nickname "Devil's Highway." This appellation arose from the profound significance of the number [666](/666_(number)) within many [Christian](/Christianity) denominations, where it is widely recognized as the [Number of the Beast](/Number_of_the_beast), a symbol of [Satan](/Satan). This pervasive satanic connotation, coupled with an alarmingly high fatality rate along the New Mexico segment of the highway, convinced a segment of the population that the road was, in fact, cursed. The problem was further exacerbated by persistent [sign theft](/Street_sign_theft), as individuals sought to possess a piece of the "Devil's Highway" legend. These combined factors ultimately spurred two distinct efforts to renumber the highway: first by officials in [Arizona](/Arizona), and subsequently by those in [New Mexico](/New_Mexico), leading to its current, less ominous numerical identity. Since the renumbering, significant safety improvement projects have been implemented along the route, and encouragingly, fatality rates have demonstrably decreased.

    The highway, now functioning as a spur route of [US 91](/U.S._Route_91) through its connection to [US 191](/U.S._Route_191), traverses the diverse landscapes of [New Mexico](/New_Mexico), [Colorado](/Colorado), and [Utah](/Utah). Its path also cuts through the sovereign tribal lands of the [Navajo Nation](/Navajo_Nation) and the [Ute Mountain Ute Tribe](/Ute_Mountain_Ute_Tribe), highlighting the rich cultural tapestry of the region. Along its course, US 491 passes by two mountains held sacred by Native American communities: [Ute Mountain](/Ute_Mountain) and the striking extinct volcanic core known as [Shiprock](/Shiprock). Other notable geographical and cultural features encountered along the route include the ancient cliff dwellings preserved within [Mesa Verde National Park](/Mesa_Verde_National_Park) and the town of [Dove Creek, Colorado](/Dove_Creek,_Colorado), which proudly proclaims itself the "pinto-bean capital of the world," a rather specific, yet charming, claim to fame. ( [Full article...](/U.S._Route_491) )

*   #### Image 18

    Healy in 1882

    [Patrick Francis Healy](/Patrick_Francis_Healy) [SJ](/Society_of_Jesus) (February 27, 1834 – January 10, 1910) was a truly remarkable figure in American history, an American [Catholic](/Catholic_Church) priest and [Jesuit](/Jesuit) whose influence on [Georgetown University](/Georgetown_University) was so profound that he became affectionately, and accurately, known as its "second founder." The university's most iconic and majestic edifice, [Healy Hall](/Healy_Hall), stands as a lasting testament to his legacy. What makes Healy's story particularly compelling is the complex interplay of identity in 19th-century America. While he [considered himself](/Self-identity) and was widely [accepted](/Passing_(racial_identity)) as [White](/White_Americans) during his lifetime, a posthumous recognition illuminated a crucial aspect of his heritage: Healy was, in fact, the first [Black American](/African_Americans) to earn a [PhD](/Doctor_of_Philosophy). Beyond this academic achievement, he also broke significant racial barriers as the first Black individual to enter the Jesuit order and, perhaps most notably, to assume the presidency of a predominantly White university.

    Healy's origins trace back to [Georgia](/Georgia_(U.S._state)), where he was born into a family that would eventually produce a notable number of Catholic leaders, a testament to their deep faith and intellectual prowess. His mother possessed [one-eighth Black](/Octoroon) ancestry, while his father was a White [Irish emigrant](/Irish_Americans). Under the draconian Georgia law of the time, Healy's father, in a cruel irony, technically held ownership of his own wife and children as [slaves](/Slavery_in_the_United_States) due to the prevailing racial codes. In a courageous and progressive act, Healy's father sent Patrick and his siblings north to be educated, providing them with opportunities denied in the South. Patrick began his higher education at the [College of the Holy Cross](/College_of_the_Holy_Cross), a foundational experience. He then continued his academic pursuits abroad, studying in Belgium at the [Catholic University of Louvain](/Catholic_University_of_Leuven_(1834%E2%80%931968)), where he ultimately achieved his doctorate in philosophy in 1864. Upon his return to America, he commenced his distinguished career at Georgetown University, initially serving as the esteemed chair of philosophy, a role that would pave the way for his transformative leadership of the institution. ( [Full article...](/Patrick_Francis_Healy) )

*   #### Image 19
    First book edition cover of The Red Badge of Courage (1895)

    [The Red Badge of Courage](/The_Red_Badge_of_Courage), an enduring classic of American literature, is an 1895 [war novel](/War_novel) penned by the remarkably insightful American author [Stephen Crane](/Stephen_Crane). The novel itself was officially published on October 3, 1895. Set against the brutal backdrop of the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War), the narrative intimately follows the journey of a young, inexperienced [private](/Private_(rank)) in the [Union Army](/Union_Army), Henry Fleming. In a moment of overwhelming fear and self-preservation, Henry flees from the chaos and carnage of the battlefield. Overcome with a profound sense of shame and searing cowardice, he subsequently yearns for a wound – a tangible, visible mark, a "red badge of courage" – that he believes could somehow counteract his perceived failings. When his regiment is once again thrust into the crucible of battle against the enemy, Henry, in a desperate bid for redemption, courageously steps forward to act as the [flag-bearer](/Flag_bearer), carrying the sacred [regimental colors](/Regimental_colors) into the fray.

    What makes Crane's novel particularly extraordinary is its profound [realism](/Literary_realism) and adherence to [naturalism](/Naturalism_(literature)), especially considering that Crane himself was born after the conclusion of the war and, at the time of writing, had not experienced the visceral horror of battle firsthand. He embarked on the creation of what would become his second novel in 1894, drawing extensively from a myriad of contemporary and historical accounts, including those previously published in periodicals like [Century Magazine](/The_Century_Magazine), which offered vivid insights into the conflict. It is widely believed by scholars and historians that Crane based the novel's fictional battle on the actual [Battle of Chancellorsville](/Battle_of_Chancellorsville), a particularly brutal engagement. Furthermore, he may have conducted interviews with veterans of the [124th New York Volunteer Infantry Regiment](/124th_New_York_Volunteer_Infantry_Regiment), a unit famously known as the Orange Blossoms, thereby imbuing his narrative with authentic human experience. Initially, the work was serialized in an abridged form in various newspapers in December 1894, generating considerable interest. The full, complete novel was then published in October 1895, solidifying its place in the literary canon. Decades later, in 1982, a longer version of the work, meticulously reconstructed from Crane's original manuscript, was finally published, offering readers an even more comprehensive glimpse into his powerful vision. ( [Full article...](/The_Red_Badge_of_Courage) )

*   #### Image 20
    The Masked Singer (abbreviated as TMS) is an American [reality singing competition](/Reality_competition) television series that burst onto the screens of [Fox](/Fox_Broadcasting_Company) on January 2, 2019. It forms an integral part of the larger [Masked Singer](/Masked_Singer) franchise, which itself originated from the wildly popular South Korean version of the show, *[King of Mask Singer](/King_of_Mask_Singer)*. The premise is delightfully absurd: celebrities, their identities meticulously concealed by elaborate, head-to-toe costumes and intricate face masks, perform songs for a panel of judges and a live audience. The program is hosted by the ever-energetic [Nick Cannon](/Nick_Cannon), and its central mystery is driven by a panel of celebrity judges who, throughout each season, endeavor to deduce the identities of the disguised singers by interpreting a series of deliberately cryptic clues. The regular panelists, [Ken Jeong](/Ken_Jeong), [Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg](/Jenny_McCarthy_Wahlberg), [Rita Ora](/Rita_Ora), and [Robin Thicke], appear in every episode, casting their votes alongside a studio audience for their favorite performances. The contestant receiving the fewest votes is then eliminated, culminating in the dramatic unmasking that reveals their true identity.

    To safeguard the meticulously guarded secrets of the celebrities' identities before each prerecorded episode is broadcast, the production employs an extensive and rather ingenious array of measures. These include the use of code names for contestants, elaborate disguises worn even off-stage, stringent [non-disclosure agreements](/Non-disclosure_agreement) signed by all involved personnel, and a dedicated team of security guards whose sole purpose is to prevent any premature revelations. While television critics have offered a somewhat mixed bag of reviews for the series, with particularly pointed negative opinions often directed at the panelists, the show's costumes have consistently garnered widespread praise. These fantastical creations, often drawing inspiration from the world of [haute couture](/Haute_couture), were designed for the first six seasons by the talented [Marina Toybina](/Marina_Toybina), whose exceptional work earned her a prestigious [Costume Designers Guild Award](/Costume_Designers_Guild) and two coveted [Creative Arts Emmy Awards](/Creative_Arts_Emmy_Award). Beyond the visual spectacle, other production staff members have also received, or been nominated for, various accolades from labor unions, a testament to the collective effort behind the show. The series itself has been honored with, or nominated for, awards presented by esteemed bodies such as the [Academy of Television Arts & Sciences](/Academy_of_Television_Arts_%26_Sciences), the [Critics Choice Association](/Critics_Choice_Association), and the [Hollywood Critics Association](/Hollywood_Critics_Association), demonstrating its significant impact within the entertainment landscape. ( [Full article...](/The_Masked_Singer_(American_TV_series)) )

*   #### Image 21
    *Casino Royale* is a 2006 [action](/Action_film) [spy thriller](/Spy_thriller) film that injected a much-needed jolt of gritty realism into the long-running James Bond franchise. It holds the distinction of being the twenty-first installment in the venerable [Eon Productions](/Eon_Productions) James Bond series, and notably, the third cinematic adaptation of [Ian Fleming](/Ian_Fleming)'s seminal 1953 [novel of the same name](/Casino_Royale_(novel)). Crucially, *Casino Royale* marked the debut of [Daniel Craig](/Daniel_Craig) in the iconic role of the fictional [MI6](/Secret_Intelligence_Service) agent [James Bond](/James_Bond_filmography), a casting choice that initially met with skepticism but ultimately revitalized the character and the series.

    This film also marked the second time [Martin Campbell](/Martin_Campbell) sat in the director's chair for a Bond film, having previously helmed *GoldenEye*. The screenplay, a collaborative effort by [Neal Purvis, Robert Wade](/Neal_Purvis_and_Robert_Wade), and [Paul Haggis](/Paul_Haggis), aimed for a more grounded and emotionally resonant narrative, stripping away some of the more fantastical elements that had crept into previous Bond iterations. Craig was joined by a formidable cast, including [Eva Green](/Eva_Green) as the enigmatic Vesper Lynd, [Mads Mikkelsen](/Mads_Mikkelsen) as the chilling villain Le Chiffre, [Judi Dench](/Judi_Dench) returning as the no-nonsense M, and [Jeffrey Wright](/Jeffrey_Wright) making his debut as Felix Leiter. The film's central plot sees Bond, recently elevated to 007 status, embarking on a critical mission: to financially cripple the ruthless [terrorism financier](/Terrorism_financing) [Le Chiffre](/Le_Chiffre). This objective is to be achieved through a high-stakes [poker](/Poker) game at the opulent Casino Royale in [Montenegro](/Montenegro), a game where the fate of global security hangs in the balance. ( [Full article...](/Casino_Royale_(2006_film)) )

*   #### Image 22

    [Solomon Porcius Sharp](/Solomon_P._Sharp) (August 22, 1787 – November 7, 1825) was an American lawyer and politician whose life, though accomplished, ended in a sensational and tragic manner. He served with distinction as [attorney general of Kentucky](/Attorney_General_of_Kentucky) and held elected positions as a member of both the [United States Congress](/United_States_Congress) and the [Kentucky General Assembly](/Kentucky_General_Assembly). His untimely murder in 1825 by [Jereboam O. Beauchamp](/Jereboam_O._Beauchamp) plunged Kentucky into a scandal that became infamous as the [Beauchamp–Sharp Tragedy](/Beauchamp%E2%80%93Sharp_Tragedy), or more colloquially, "The Kentucky Tragedy," a lurid tale that captivated the nation and has inspired numerous literary works.

    Sharp embarked on his political journey representing [Warren County](/Warren_County,_Kentucky) in the [Kentucky House of Representatives](/Kentucky_House_of_Representatives), where he quickly established himself. He briefly interrupted his legislative career to serve in the [War of 1812](/War_of_1812), demonstrating a commitment to military service. Upon his return to [Kentucky](/Kentucky), his political fortunes continued to rise, and he was elected to the [U.S. House of Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives) in 1813. He secured re-election for a second term, but his support for a highly controversial bill concerning legislator salaries ultimately cost him his seat in 1816, illustrating the precarious nature of public opinion. Aligned with Kentucky's Debt Relief Party, Sharp made a political comeback, returning to the Kentucky House in 1817. In 1821, he accepted Governor [John Adair](/John_Adair)'s appointment to the significant post of Attorney General of Kentucky, a role he performed with dedication. Adair's successor, [Joseph Desha](/Joseph_Desha), recognizing Sharp's capabilities, re-appointed him to this position. In 1825, Sharp resigned as attorney general, once again returning to the Kentucky House, a move that, tragically, placed him in the path of his assassin. His murder remains one of the most enduring and dark chapters in Kentucky's political history. ( [Full article...](/Solomon_P._Sharp) )

*   #### Image 23
    "[Jihad](/Jihad_(song))" is a track by the American [thrash metal](/Thrash_metal) band [Slayer](/Slayer), featured on their 2006 studio album, *[Christ Illusion](/Christ_Illusion)*. The song is notable for its controversial lyrical content, as it deliberately adopts the chilling perspective of a terrorist who actively participated in the horrific [September 11, 2001 attacks](/September_11,_2001_attacks). The track culminates with spoken lyrics directly transcribed from words left behind by [Mohamed Atta](/Mohamed_Atta), the individual identified by the [FBI](/Federal_Bureau_of_Investigation) as the "head suicide terrorist" responsible for piloting the first plane into the World Trade Center. The primary musical composition for "Jihad" was crafted by guitarist [Jeff Hanneman](/Jeff_Hanneman), with the lyrics co-authored by Hanneman and vocalist [Tom Araya](/Tom_Araya).

    Upon its release, "Jihad" received a predictably mixed reception from the music press, with reviews almost universally focusing on the highly contentious and sensitive subject matter of its lyrics. The song inevitably drew comparisons to Slayer's earlier, equally provocative 1986 track, "[Angel of Death](/Angel_of_Death_(Slayer_song))" – another Hanneman-penned composition – which similarly ignited outrage and debate at the time of its release, showcasing the band's consistent willingness to confront uncomfortable and controversial themes through their art. ( [Full article...](/Jihad_(song)) )

*   #### Image 24
    [Joseph Benson Foraker](/Joseph_B._Foraker) (July 5, 1846 – May 10, 1917) was a prominent American politician affiliated with the [Republican Party](/Republican_Party_(United_States)). His career saw him serve as the 37th [governor of Ohio](/Governor_of_Ohio) from 1886 to 1890, and subsequently as a distinguished [United States senator](/United_States_senator) representing [Ohio](/Ohio) from 1897 until 1909. Foraker's political trajectory was marked by both success and significant ideological shifts within his party.

    Born in rural Ohio, Foraker's early life was profoundly shaped by the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War). At the tender age of 16, he enlisted in the [Union Army](/Union_Army), demonstrating a remarkable commitment to the Union cause. He served with distinction for almost three years, steadily rising through the ranks to attain the commission of captain. Following the cessation of hostilities, Foraker pursued higher education, becoming a member of [Cornell University](/Cornell_University)'s inaugural graduating class, a testament to his intellectual drive. He then embarked on a legal career, establishing himself as a lawyer. His reputation as a compelling political speaker grew, leading to his election as a judge in 1879. His first attempt at the governorship in 1883 proved unsuccessful, but his persistence paid off two years later when he secured election to the office. As Ohio's governor, Foraker forged a powerful, if ultimately fragile, alliance with the formidable Republican Party "boss," [Mark Hanna](/Mark_Hanna). However, this alliance fractured in 1888, highlighting the internecine struggles within the Republican Party. Foraker faced defeat in his bid for re-election in 1889. Despite this setback, he successfully returned to the national political stage, elected as a U.S. senator by the [Ohio General Assembly](/Ohio_General_Assembly) in 1896, following an earlier, unsuccessful attempt at that office in 1892. His career thus demonstrates a resilience and a knack for navigating the complex currents of late 19th and early 20th-century American politics. ( [Full article...](/Joseph_B._Foraker) )

*   #### Image 25

    Official portrait, c. 1870s

    [Thomas Francis Bayard](/Thomas_F._Bayard) (October 29, 1828 – September 28, 1898) was an eminent American lawyer, politician, and diplomat hailing from [Wilmington, Delaware](/Wilmington,_Delaware). A staunch [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)), Bayard served an impressive three terms as a [United States Senator](/United_States_Senate) representing Delaware, and, with notable persistence, made three unsuccessful bids for the Democratic nomination for President of the United States. His political career reached its zenith in 1885 when President [Grover Cleveland](/Grover_Cleveland) appointed him to the prestigious and influential position of [Secretary of State](/United_States_Secretary_of_State). After a four-year interlude in private life, Bayard returned to the diplomatic arena, accepting the significant post of [Ambassador to Great Britain](/United_States_Ambassador_to_the_United_Kingdom), a testament to his continued influence and the respect he commanded.

    Born into a distinguished Delaware family with a deep tradition of public service, Bayard's political education began at home, learning the intricacies of statesmanship from his father, [James A. Bayard Jr.](/James_A._Bayard_Jr.), who also served with distinction in the Senate. In 1869, the Delaware legislature, recognizing his burgeoning talent, elected Bayard to the Senate upon his father's retirement, effectively passing the torch of political leadership. As a [Peace Democrat](/Peace_Democrat) during the tumultuous [Civil War](/American_Civil_War), Bayard spent his early years in the Senate in vocal opposition to [Republican](/History_of_the_Republican_Party_(United_States)) policies, particularly those related to the controversial [Reconstruction](/Reconstruction_Era) of the defeated Confederate states. His deeply conservative leanings extended to financial matters; he became a fervent proponent of the [gold standard](/Gold_standard) and a vocal opponent of [greenbacks](/United_States_Note) and [silver coinage](/Silver_coinage), which he adamantly believed would inevitably lead to rampant [inflation](/Inflation). Bayard's steadfast conservative politics garnered him considerable popularity in the [Southern United States](/Southern_United_States) and among powerful financial interests in the [Eastern United States](/Eastern_United_States). However, this regional and specialized support never quite translated into the broader appeal necessary to secure the Democratic nomination for president, despite his determined attempts in 1876, 1880, and 1884. His career embodies a particular brand of principled, if ultimately limited, political power in post-Civil War America. ( [Full article...](/Thomas_F._Bayard) )

