[Stephen Grover Cleveland](/Grover_Cleveland) (March 18, 1837 – June 24, 1908) occupies a rather unique and often perplexing position in American presidential history. He served as both the [22nd and 24th President of the United States](/List_of_Presidents_of_the_United_States), a distinction that makes him the only president to hold two non-consecutive terms. Consequently, he is the sole individual counted twice in the official numbering of the presidents, a bureaucratic anomaly for a rather unanomalous man. Cleveland also holds the impressive record of winning the [popular vote](/Elections_in_the_United_States) for president on three separate occasions—in [1884](/1884_United_States_presidential_election), [1888](/1888_United_States_presidential_election), and [1892](/1892_United_States_presidential_election). Furthermore, he was the singular [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) to be elected to the presidency during the protracted era of [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) political dominance, which spanned from 1860 to 1912, a true political outlier.

Cleveland was the undisputed leader of the pro-business faction known as the [Bourbon Democrats](/Bourbon_Democrats). This group vehemently opposed high tariffs, the inflationary push for [free silver](/Free_silver), unchecked [inflation](/Inflation) in general, the growing calls for [imperialism](/Overseas_expansion_of_the_United_States), and any form of [subsidies](/Subsidy) directed towards businesses, farmers, or veterans. His relentless battles for political reform and a stringent fiscal conservatism cemented his legacy as an icon for American conservatives, even if his methods were often unpopular. His second term, however, coincided with the devastating [Panic of 1893](/Panic_of_1893), a severe national economic depression that Cleveland, despite his efforts, was unable to reverse. This economic catastrophe effectively shattered his Democratic party, paving the way for overwhelming Republican landslides in the 1894 and 1896 elections, and ultimately leading to the agrarian and silverite wings seizing control of his party in 1896, a humiliating defeat for the old guard.

Cleveland was a man who took strong, often unyielding, positions, and in turn, he endured heavy criticism, seemingly unfazed by public disapproval. His controversial intervention in the [Pullman Strike](/Pullman_Strike) of 1894, undertaken to ensure the unimpeded movement of the nation's railroads, infuriated labor unions across the country and alienated his own party in Illinois. Similarly, his steadfast support for the [gold standard](/Gold_standard) and his resolute opposition to [free silver](/Free_silver) deeply alienated the powerful [agrarian](/Agrarianism) wing of the Democratic Party, further fracturing his political base. Biographer [Allan Nevins](/Allan_Nevins), in a rather insightful assessment, penned that "in Grover Cleveland the greatness lies in typical rather than unusual qualities. He had no endowments that thousands of men do not have. He possessed honesty, courage, firmness, independence, and common sense. But he possessed them to a degree other men do not." A rather backhanded compliment, suggesting his virtues were common, just exceptionally strong.

