*   #### Image 1

    [Surrender of General Burgoyne](/Surrender_of_General_Burgoyne)
    Engraving credit: Frederick Girsch, [Bureau of Engraving and Printing](/Bureau_of_Engraving_and_Printing); restored by [Andrew Shiva](/User:Godot13)

    This image presents an engraved vignette, a smaller, focused rendition, of the American artist [John Trumbull](/John_Trumbull)'s monumental 1821 oil-on-canvas painting, famously titled *[Surrender of General Burgoyne](/Surrender_of_General_Burgoyne)*. The scene depicted is a pivotal moment in the nascent history of the [United States](/United_States): the formal surrender of British troops, under the command of [John Burgoyne](/John_Burgoyne), on October 17, 1777. This event marked the decisive conclusion of the [Saratoga campaign](/Saratoga_campaign) during the [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War). This particular work is one of eight significant historical paintings that grace the walls of [the rotunda](/United_States_Capitol_rotunda) within the [United States Capitol](/United_States_Capitol) in Washington, D.C., serving as a constant visual reminder of foundational national moments. The American victory [at Saratoga](/Battles_of_Saratoga) had profound and far-reaching consequences for the trajectory of the war. While some foreign powers, most notably [France](/France), had already been discreetly supporting the American cause with financial and material provisions, the French government had remained hesitant to commit to full-scale, open involvement. However, the undeniable strategic significance of the capture of an entire British army at Saratoga by American forces compelled them to critically re-evaluate their level of commitment, ultimately leading to a crucial alliance. This specific [line engraving](/Line_engraving) was produced for the [Bureau of Engraving and Printing](/Bureau_of_Engraving_and_Printing) (BEP), intended for utilitarian yet symbolic use on [United States](/United_States) banknotes, embedding this historical triumph into the very currency of the nation.

