*   #### Image 2

    [Denver](/Denver)
    Photograph: [William Henry Jackson](/William_Henry_Jackson); Restoration: [Bammesk](/User:Bammesk)

    [Denver](/Denver), the capital and most populous municipality of the U.S. state of [Colorado](/Colorado), sprawls across the [South Platte River Valley](/South_Platte_River), nestled on the western edge of the [High Plains](/High_Plains_(United_States)), with the majestic [Front Range](/Front_Range) of the [Rocky Mountains](/Rocky_Mountains) rising dramatically just to its east. Established in 1858, the city bears the name of [James W. Denver](/James_W._Denver), a former governor of the [Kansas Territory](/Kansas_Territory). It proudly carries the [nickname](/List_of_city_nicknames_in_the_United_States) "the Mile High City," a designation earned from its official elevation, which stands precisely one mile (5280 feet or 1609.3 meters) above sea level. Initially a part of [Arapahoe County](/Arapahoe_County,_Colorado), Denver underwent a significant administrative transformation in 1902, becoming a [consolidated city-county](/Consolidated_city-county), a structural arrangement that merged its municipal and county governance.

    This particular image offers a panoramic vista of Denver around the year 1898, captured from the commanding vantage point atop the [Colorado State Capitol](/Colorado_State_Capitol). The perspective looks northwest, tracing the length of 16th Street as it recedes into the distance. Prominently visible on the left is the domed structure that once housed the Arapahoe County Courthouse, a building that was ultimately demolished in 1933. To the right, the elegant presence of the [Brown Palace Hotel](/Brown_Palace_Hotel_(Denver)) can be discerned, a landmark that continues to define the city's architectural heritage. The photograph serves as a fascinating historical document, capturing the city during a period of rapid growth and transformation, a testament to its enduring spirit of expansion.

