*   #### Image 3

    [Utah Territory](/Utah_Territory)
    Illustration credit: Henry Mitchell; restored by [Andrew Shiva](/User:Godot13)

    The [Utah Territory](/Utah_Territory) was a distinct [U.S. territory](/Territories_of_the_United_States) situated in the vast expanse of the [Western United States](/Western_United_States). Its existence began with its official creation on September 9, 1850, and it persisted as a territory until its eventual admission to the Union on January 4, 1896, at which point it became the [State of Utah](/Utah). This particular image showcases the historical coat of arms of the Utah Territory, as meticulously illustrated by the American engraver Henry Mitchell. This illustration appeared in his notable work, *[State Arms of the Union](/Historical_armorial_of_U.S._states_from_1876)*, which was published in 1876 by [Louis Prang](/Louis_Prang). The central element of the [escutcheon](/Escutcheon_(heraldry)) depicts a beehive, a powerful and enduring symbol chosen to represent the industrious and hard-working inhabitants of the nascent state, reflecting their pioneering spirit and dedication. Complementing this, [sego lilies](/Calochortus_nuttallii) are also prominently featured, symbolizing peace and resilience in the rugged Western landscape. The design as a whole encapsulated the aspirations and values of the people and the territory as it moved towards statehood.

