    This striking 1885 [lithograph](/Lithograph) offers a captivating bird's-eye view of the city of [Phoenix, Arizona](/Phoenix,_Arizona), capturing its nascent form decades before it would burgeon into the [fifth-most-populous city in the United States](/List_of_United_States_cities_by_population). The city's founding in 1868 was a deliberate act of rebirth, established on the very site of lands that had once been cultivated and inhabited by the ancient [Hohokam](/Hohokam people), a civilization that had, mysteriously, abandoned the area approximately 400 years prior to the arrival of modern settlers. The name "Phoenix" was chosen with considerable foresight and symbolic resonance, perfectly describing a new city rising, quite literally, from the ruins and remnants of a former, forgotten civilization, much like the mythical bird regenerating from ashes. The lithograph provides a valuable historical snapshot, illustrating the early layout and development of a city destined for significant growth and transformation in the arid landscape of the American Southwest.

