*   #### Image 7

    [Bryce Canyon National Park](/Bryce_Canyon_National_Park)
    Photo credit: [Daniel Mayer](/User:Maveric149)

    [Bryce Canyon National Park](/Bryce_Canyon_National_Park) is a truly remarkable [national park](/National_park) nestled in the southwestern expanse of [Utah](/Utah) in the [United States](/United_States). The park's most iconic feature is, of course, Bryce Canyon itself – a colossal natural [amphitheater](/Amphitheater) that has been sculpted over millennia by the relentless forces of [erosion](/Erosion) along the eastern flank of the [Paunsaugunt Plateau](/Paunsaugunt_Plateau). It's a geological marvel, but here's a rather inconvenient truth: despite its name, Bryce Canyon is not, technically speaking, a true [canyon](/Canyon). This is because its formation did not originate from [erosion](/Erosion) initiated by a central [stream](/Stream) or river carving its way through the landscape. Instead, it's a series of intricately carved, horseshoe-shaped natural amphitheaters, each brimming with thousands of unique geological structures known as hoodoos. These fantastical spires, pinnacles, and fins, painted in vibrant hues of orange, red, and white, are the result of frost wedging and chemical weathering, creating a landscape that feels almost otherworldly.

