*   #### Image 8

    Check used for the [Alaska Purchase](/Alaska_Purchase)
    Check: [William H. Seward](/William_H._Seward); scan: Our Documents initiative

    This is the very [check](/Cheque) that sealed one of the most significant, and initially controversial, land deals in American history: the [Alaska Purchase](/Alaska_Purchase). Issued on the first day of August in 1868, this financial instrument bears the signature of the then-U.S. Secretary of State, [William H. Seward](/William_H._Seward), whose vision and persistence were instrumental in the transaction. For a total sum of $7.2 million – a figure that, at the time, many Americans considered an exorbitant waste for a frozen wasteland – the [United States](/United_States) government acquired [Russian America](/Russian_America) from the [Russian Empire](/Russian_Empire). The latter was represented in the transaction by its Minister to the [United States](/United_States), [Eduard de Stoeckl](/Eduard_de_Stoeckl). The vast, untamed lands involved in this purchase would eventually, in 1959, be formally admitted to the Union as the modern state of [Alaska](/Alaska), proving to be an immensely valuable acquisition, rich in natural resources and strategic importance, despite the initial public skepticism. This check represents a tangible link to that pivotal moment of territorial expansion.

