*   #### Image 9

    [Inauguration of John Tyler](/Inauguration_of_John_Tyler)
    Engraving credit: [Bureau of Engraving and Printing](/Bureau_of_Engraving_and_Printing); restored by [Andrew Shiva](/User:Godot13)

    This engraving depicts the rather unprecedented [inauguration of John Tyler](/Inauguration_of_John_Tyler) as the tenth [president of the United States](/President_of_the_United_States), an event that unfolded on April 6, 1841, in Washington, D.C. What made this particular ceremony historically significant was its context: it followed the sudden and unexpected death of President [William Henry Harrison](/William_Henry_Harrison) just two days prior. Consequently, this marked the first non-scheduled, extraordinary [presidential inauguration](/United_States_presidential_inauguration) to ever take place in American history, setting a precedent for vice presidential succession. Upon receiving the somber news of Harrison's passing, Tyler embarked on a swift and urgent journey to Washington from his home in [Williamsburg, Virginia](/Williamsburg,_Virginia). Utilizing the fastest means of conveyance available at the time – a combination of steamboat and train – he completed the journey in a remarkable 21 hours, a testament to the urgency of the moment and the nascent transportation infrastructure of the era. The image captures a moment of both solemnity and constitutional transition.

