*   #### Image 10

    [Bessie Coleman](/Bessie_Coleman)
    Photograph credit: Unknown

    [Bessie Coleman](/Bessie_Coleman) (1892–1926) was a pioneering [civil aviator](/Civil_aviation) whose indomitable spirit shattered racial and gender barriers in the early days of flight. On June 15, 1921, she achieved a truly historic milestone, becoming the first African-American woman and, notably, the first Native American to earn an aviation pilot's license. Her path to the skies was not easy; facing systemic discrimination and denied opportunities in the [United States](/United_States) due to both her race and her sex, Coleman refused to be deterred. Instead, she courageously sought training abroad, traveling to [France](/France) to learn to fly, a testament to her unwavering determination. Her burgeoning career was defined by thrilling stunt flying and captivating performances in [air shows](/Air_show), where she quickly earned the moniker "Queen Bess." Tragically, her life and career were cut short in 1926 when she was thrown from a plane mid-air during a test flight, a devastating accident that ended her remarkable journey. Her untimely death meant that her ambitious dream of establishing a school specifically for young black aviators went unaccomplished. Nevertheless, her groundbreaking achievements and relentless pursuit of her passion served as an enduring and powerful inspiration for an entire generation of African-American men and women, demonstrating that the sky, indeed, was not the limit.

