    [Chester A. Arthur](/Chester_A._Arthur) (October 5, 1829 – November 18, 1886) was an American attorney and politician who unexpectedly found himself serving as the 21st [President of the United States](/President_of_the_United_States) from 1881 to 1885. Born in [Vermont](/Vermont) and raised in upstate [New York](/New_York_(state)), Arthur initially pursued a legal career in [New York City](/New_York_City). His public service began during the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War), where he served as a [quartermaster general](/Quartermaster_general), demonstrating administrative acumen. Following the war, he became actively involved in the [Republican party](/Republican_Party_(United_States)), steadily rising through its ranks. His ascent culminated in his election as vice president on the ticket with President [James A. Garfield](/James_A._Garfield). Fate, however, intervened dramatically: Arthur assumed the presidency upon Garfield's tragic [assassination](/Assassination_of_James_A._Garfield) just six months into his term, an unforeseen and heavy responsibility.

    During his presidency, Arthur, perhaps surprisingly given his past as a Stalwart Republican, championed and successfully implemented a significant [reform of the civil service](/Pendleton_Civil_Service_Reform_Act), a crucial step towards merit-based government employment. He also oversaw important [navy reform](/History_of_the_United_States_Navy), modernizing the fleet. Additionally, his administration enacted a controversial but significant piece of legislation: [an act](/Chinese_Exclusion_Act) that prohibited immigration by Chinese laborers and, further, denied citizenship to those already residing in the [United States](/United_States). This act reflected the prevailing xenophobia of the era. Due to his declining health, Arthur, with a pragmatic understanding of his limitations, made the decision not to seek a second term. His presidency, though short and unexpected, left a notable mark on American governance and policy.

