    This image captures the terrifying genesis of the atomic age: the [Trinity nuclear test](/Trinity_(nuclear_test)) explosion, frozen at a mere 0.016 seconds after detonation. At this infinitesimal moment, the fireball, a nascent sun on Earth, had already expanded to an astonishing width of approximately 200 meters (700 feet). This epoch-defining event, conducted by the [United States](/United_States) on July 16, 1945, took place at a remote site 35 miles (56 kilometers) southeast of [Socorro, New Mexico](/Socorro,_New_Mexico), a location now famously part of the [White Sands Missile Range](/White_Sands_Missile_Range). Trinity was not just any [test](/Nuclear_testing); it was the inaugural test of the technology underpinning a [nuclear weapon](/Nuclear_weapon), specifically an implosion-design plutonium device. The success of this experiment irrevocably altered the course of human history, ushering in the atomic era and forever changing the nature of warfare and global power dynamics. The photograph itself is a stark, almost abstract, representation of raw, unfathomable power unleashed.

