    This image depicts a woman diligently operating a [Hollerith pantograph](/Keypunch), a remarkable machine developed by the visionary [Herman Hollerith](/Herman_Hollerith). This ingenious device was designed for the precise punching of cards, a process that generated machine-readable [data](/Data). This data, once encoded, could then be efficiently processed by other mechanical means, heralding a new era of information management. Such pioneering tools were deployed with considerable success during the [1890 United States census](/1890_United_States_census), an undertaking of immense logistical complexity. This marked a significant historical milestone: it was the very first occasion that the [country's census](/United_States_census) data was tabulated not by laborious manual methods, but by machine, dramatically reducing the time and effort required for such a vast statistical compilation. The image serves as a fascinating snapshot of early automation and its profound impact on large-scale data processing.

