*   #### Image 15

    [Charles J. Guiteau](/Charles_J._Guiteau)
    Cartoon: James Wales; Restoration: [Jujutacular](/User:Jujutacular)

    This 1881 [editorial cartoon](/Editorial_cartoon) offers a rather pointed and critical depiction of [Charles J. Guiteau](/Charles_J._Guiteau), an American lawyer whose name is indelibly linked to one of the darkest moments in U.S. presidential history: the [assassination of President James A. Garfield](/James_A._Garfield_assassination) on July 2, 1881. Guiteau, shown here clutching a note ominously declaring "An office or your life!", harbored a delusionally inflated sense of his own importance. He genuinely believed that his political support had been largely instrumental in Garfield's electoral victory and, consequently, felt entitled to a diplomatic appointment, specifically an [ambassadorship](/Ambassador), as a reward. His persistent and increasingly aggressive requests for this coveted position were, however, repeatedly and firmly rejected by the Garfield administration. Despite the subsequent use of the [insanity defense](/Insanity_defense) during his highly publicized trial, Guiteau was ultimately found guilty of murder. He met his end by [hanging](/Hanging) on June 30, 1882, a grim conclusion to a life marked by ambition, delusion, and ultimately, an act of profound violence that shook the nation.

