[Judy Garland](/Judy_Garland) (June 10, 1922 – June 22, 1969) was far more than an American actress and singer; she was a phenomenon, a talent whose luminous career spanned 45 of her tragically short 47 years. Garland achieved international superstardom, captivating audiences in a diverse array of musical and dramatic roles on screen, as a celebrated [recording artist](/Musician), and as an electrifying presence on the concert stage. Her versatility was widely respected and acknowledged, earning her a Juvenile [Academy Award](/Academy_Award) for her early contributions, a [Golden Globe Award](/Golden_Globe_Award), the prestigious [Cecil B. DeMille Award](/Golden_Globe_Cecil_B._DeMille_Award) for her monumental body of work in films, as well as multiple [Grammy Awards](/Grammy_Award) and a special, well-deserved [Tony Award](/Special_Tony_Award).

Yet, beneath the glittering facade of professional triumph, Garland waged a relentless and often losing battle against profound personal demons throughout her life. She harbored deep insecurities about her appearance, feelings that were cruelly exacerbated by powerful film executives who, with a callous disregard for her well-being, told her she was unattractive and relentlessly manipulated her on-screen physical appearance to fit their narrow ideals. Beyond these emotional wounds, Garland was perpetually plagued by financial instability, often finding herself owing hundreds of thousands of dollars in [back taxes](/Back_taxes), a testament to the exploitative nature of the studio system and her own struggles with managing wealth. Her personal life was equally tumultuous; she married five times, with her first four marriages ultimately ending in divorce, leaving a trail of broken promises and emotional upheaval. Tragically, Judy Garland died of an accidental [drug overdose](/Drug_overdose) at the age of 47, leaving behind her beloved children: [Liza Minnelli](/Liza_Minnelli), [Lorna Luft](/Lorna_Luft), and Joey Luft.

Her legacy, however, has only grown in stature since her death. In 1997, Garland was posthumously honored with a [Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award](/Grammy_Lifetime_Achievement_Award), a recognition of her enduring impact on music. Several of her iconic recordings have been deservedly inducted into the esteemed [Grammy Hall of Fame](/Grammy_Hall_of_Fame_Award). And in 1999, the prestigious [American Film Institute](/American_Film_Institute) cemented her place in cinematic history, placing her among the ten [greatest female stars](/AFI%27s_100_Years%E2%80%A6100_Stars) in the history of [American cinema](/Cinema_of_the_United_States). A life of immense talent and profound sorrow, forever etched into the cultural consciousness.

