*   ### Selected location -
    *   show another

    Here, a glimpse into a corner of the [United States](/United_States) that, perhaps, hasn't yet been entirely paved over.

[Brockway Mountain Drive](/Brockway_Mountain_Drive) is an impressive 8.883-mile (14.296-kilometer) scenic highway that gracefully winds through the picturesque [Keweenaw Peninsula](/Keweenaw_Peninsula) of [Michigan](/Michigan). It is situated just to the west of the charming, albeit often frigid, community of [Copper Harbor](/Copper_Harbor,_Michigan). Motorists can access this breathtaking route from [M-26](/M-26_(Michigan_highway)) at either its western terminus near [Eagle Harbor](/Eagle_Harbor,_Michigan) or its eastern entrance close to Copper Harbor. The drive itself follows the dramatic ridge of Brockway Mountain, an elevated feature created by the formidable [Keweenaw Fault](/Keweenaw_Fault). Along its course, the road ascends to a remarkable height of 1,320 feet (402 meters) above sea level, placing it a significant 720 feet (220 meters) above the glistening surface of [Lake Superior](/Lake_Superior), offering unparalleled vistas.

Numerous strategically placed turnouts along the route invite travelers to pause and absorb the panoramic views of Copper Harbor, the vast expanse of Lake Superior, and the seemingly endless stretches of undeveloped woodland. On a particularly clear day, the distant contours of [Isle Royale](/Isle_Royale) can be discerned, lying some 50 miles (80 kilometers) away across the immense lake, a testament to the exceptional visibility from this elevated vantage point. Brockway Mountain itself bears the name of David D. Brockway, one of the pioneering residents who settled in this rugged area. The construction of the road was an initiative undertaken by the county road commission, significantly aided by funding secured through [Depression](/Great_Depression)-era work programs in 1933, providing much-needed employment during a difficult economic period. For a brief time after its completion, it served as a crucial connection for the parallel state highway. Since its grand opening, Brockway Mountain Drive has consistently garnered recognition in various publications and other media for its inherent scenic beauty, a reputation that dates back to the mid-20th century. Newspaper profiles focusing on [Keweenaw County](/Keweenaw_County,_Michigan) or the broader [Upper Peninsula](/Upper_Peninsula_of_Michigan) frequently highlight the exceptional scenic value of this roadway and its surrounding pristine natural environment, drawing visitors to this remote, beautiful corner of the [United States](/United_States).

