*   ### Selected cuisines, dishes and foods -
    *   show another

    Multi-colored [flint corn](/Flint_corn)

    The [cuisine of New England](/Cuisine_of_New_England) is a distinctive branch of [American cuisine](/Cuisine_of_the_United_States), a culinary tradition that germinated and evolved within the historical [New England](/New_England) region of the [United States](/United_States). Its deep roots trace back to a fascinating confluence of influences: the traditional [English cuisine](/English_cuisine) brought by early European settlers, and the rich, indigenous culinary practices of various [Native American tribes](/Indigenous_cuisine_of_the_Americas), including the [Abenaki](/Abenaki), [Narragansett](/Narragansett_people), [Niantic](/Niantic_people), [Wabanaki](/Wabanaki_Confederacy), and [Wampanoag](/Wampanoag) peoples, among others. Over centuries, this foundational blend was further enriched by subsequent waves of immigration, incorporating flavors and techniques from [Irish](/Irish_cuisine), [French-Canadian](/Cuisine_of_Quebec), [Italian](/Italian_cuisine), and [Portuguese](/Portuguese_cuisine) cuisines, to name just a few.

    Characteristically, New England cuisine is defined by its generous and often ingenious use of [potatoes](/Potato), various types of [beans](/Bean), a diverse range of [dairy products](/Dairy_product), and, perhaps most prominently, an abundance of fresh [seafood](/Seafood). This strong reliance on marine bounty is a direct historical consequence of the region's geographical position, with its numerous seaports and a flourishing [fishing](/Fishing) industry that has sustained its communities for generations. [Corn](/Maize), a staple crop historically cultivated by Native American tribes throughout New England, continues to be grown in all the New England states. While [sweet corn](/Sweet_corn) is the most common variety today, [flint corn](/Flint_corn) is also cultivated, often for more traditional applications. This versatile grain is classically utilized in hearty [hasty puddings](/Hasty_pudding), comforting [cornbreads](/Cornbread), and rich, savory [corn chowders](/Corn_chowder), embodying the enduring culinary heritage of the region. ( [Full article...](/Cuisine_of_New_England) )

